I used this app to transfer the contents of a 200gig memory card over my 
wifi network from a Samsung tablet to an nvidia shield pro media server 
hard drive. The music folder on the card was nearly 100gig on its own, and 
I have been trying to copy the files by a variety of different ways none of 
which could handle the file sizes. This app did the lot in one go in less 
than five hours. That's the upside tho cause the app is NOT very user 
friendly and comes with no instructions worth talking about. It is intended 
for the technically inclined which is really a shame cause if you know what 
you are doing it does exactly what it doesn't say on the tin. A very useful 
tool none the less though .

The app is good over all but aggressive with its license on android (not ios), making it virtually unusable unless the Internet works flawlessly, not WiFi, the Internet, meaning you can't use a router when the phone lines are down, or a portable router with no reception, or anything like that it kinda ruins the whole app. Separately, I'd read on another site that this app had the option of utilising Bluetooth (not present)and local networks between devices (unless stable Internet connection is present perhaps). This error does not occur on the ios version, so this is disappointingly limited to android, its simple, give a 24 hour license check if you want, but an incessant warning will not leave you alone for more than a second is so aggravating (it is however, still possible to use the app if you click what you want in the split second before it reappears).

I've been using this File Transfer Pro app for quite a while and I think it's great for transferring files to or from my desktop PC from a MS Surface pro PC, an Nvidia Shield K1 table, and a new Samsung Galaxy S8+ cell phone.  I mainly use it to transfer large screen recording MP4s from the phone or tablet to my desktop PC or the Surface PC. I was surprised when it found the new S8+ phone without doing anything other than installing the app on the phone.  The screen recording MP4s usually consist of flights with the Mavic Pro quadcopter which are quite large and transfer the MP4s over my local network and they transfer  anywhere from 30 to 50 mbps I tried a few other ways to transfer files that were way to complicated and not very dependable but this app is easy, fast, and dependable.  Disclaimer:  I have no connection to the app developers and paid for this app like everyone else.
